defaultHow do Government and local authorities identify demand for passenger transport in isolated communities (including rural and urban areas defaultand island communities)?default 
default&#xa0;
default1. At present demand is largely calculated from existing usage/ actual ridership figures supplied by the operators. We are aware of only a very few instances where bus companies or local authorities have carried out market resear
defaultch to identify 
defaultpotential
default demand as a result of new housing developments, new employment opportunities, or to identify opportunities to reduce existing traffic congestion.
default&#xa0;
default2. We believe that there are opportunities for closer partnership between bus compan
defaulties and highways authorities, and between neighbouring local authorities, to share statistics for road congestion, proposed new employment areas, strategic housing sites etc, and thus analyse the potential for major 
defaultcommercial 
defaultroutes, with the rural routes
default serving as feeder services. 
default&#xa0;
default3. This was illustrated well in a consultation on bus provision in B
defaultath and North East Somerset three 
defaultyears ago. This was run by 
defaultHalcrow
default on behalf of First 
defaultUK 
defaultBus, where a feature identified in the session with the major empl
defaultoyers was that major opportunities for improved services to those employers had not ever been market surveyed.  It has still not been carried out, despite requests from those employers. 
default&#xa0;
default4. Local authorities, and particularly groups of local authorities w
defaultith a "bigger strategic picture" of travel, employment and educational needs, are in the ideal position to see how the various elements of rural transport demand can be aggregated to make up a commercial, or at least less expensive, network of services. 
defaultH
defaultowever such integration has not been active post-privatisation, and there is at present no strategic planning platform for such joined up working between rural and urban areas. or between neighbouring authorities. Furthermore it will require a breaking dow
defaultn of the existing departmental separations, as between education and social services, to identify mutual benefits and savings.
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is suggested that the 
defaultnew local enterprise partnerships 
defaultcould assist local authorities in cooperation between authorities, by
default recognising the wider economic benefits of meeting the social and health roles of rural public transport
default&#xa0;
default5. There is further the complication of the removal of 
defaultformer 
defaultcross subsidy between services, so that profitable routes continue to be run to the b
defaultenefit of the private provider while more costly rural routes (which may in themselves enable travellers to access and contribute to the success of the commercially operated ones) continue only through subsidy from the local authority.
