defaultHow effectively do Community Transport services address the needs of passengers in isolated communities? How could Community Transport be improved? default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default10. There are good examples in some local authority areas.  However these are largely dependent upon voluntary support, and the variation of quality between authority areas is not considered to be acceptable. For users of such services improvement comes fr
defaultom certainty of provision, resulting in an ability to make appointments with confidence. 
default&#xa0;
default
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTo what extent should passengers in isolated communities be expected to rely on taxis and other demand-responsive transport services? default&#xa0;
default11. While taxi services might appear to be a solution, the economics of taxi provision rule this out as meeting rural needs. 
default              
default- Successful taxi services rely upon short "downtime" , and the ability to find return fares. 
default              
default- Rural taxi providers often depe
defaultnd upon alternative sources of income, which in turn limit their availability to provide taxi services to certain times of day
default 
default              
default- People requiring transport are often those on low wages (
defaulte.g.
default farm/ rural business workers, care providers, cleaners, those o
defaultn basic pension, the elderly ) who cannot afford regular taxi travel.
default              
default- Taxis do not meet the needs of those under driving age who seek access to leisure or employment, 
defaulte.g.
default children wanting to go to a leisure facility in holiday periods or young people s
defaulteeking part time employment
